,Not Recommended,303800,20040268,"Posted: 28 December, 2015",all,<™[-=> Cookiez <=-]™>,"$3.15, an okay price for the game. This is an unfair review as I am slightly partial to CD Projekt Red's Witcher series. There are some flaws with the game design, such as multiplayer solitaire. I tried using Triss Merigold and she seemed fine. However, after playing multiple games, I've decided to vote it down, mainly due to the insane random events from dice rolling and card drawing.PROS1. Follows the Witcher SeriesVery accurate, all the main characters are inside. I was actually looking forward to using the Scoia'tael (Elves), Philippa Eilhart (Mage ♥♥♥♥♥) or Saskia (Dragoness) in the game.2. IntuitiveIt's easy to learn. I didn't play a single tutorial to be able to understand the game.CONS1. Multiplayer Solitaire *****You don't really care about any other player as none of actions matter to you. There is hardly any player interaction.2. Advanced Snakes and Ladders *****It is just personal racing like advanced Snakes and Ladders. You just roll dice and play the game on your own.3. Random Monsters and CombatThis is so boring. The random monster generation doesn't capture the fantastic monsters that I experienced playing the Witcher 2. To defeat SINGLE monsters, you roll Swords and Shields. If you roll a sufficient amount of Swords, you kill the monster. If you roll a sufficient amount of Shields, you block its negative effect.It lacks the skilled planning and excitement that the normal Witcher game brings since it all boils down to Sword and Shield.4. Random Bad Fortune and Investigation CardsSome just make you lose 2 VP just for drawing them and some just do nothing. The randomness is horrendous. The investigation cards are also full of negative cards called Setbacks which have no redeeming value. If you draw badly, you are screwed.SUGGESTIONS1. TrapsIf you arrive in a location, you can play a card that leaves a surprise for the next player who crosses (not land) its path. It might be a nasty surprise or a simple challenge. That way players will look at where other players are moving to.2. Learning Other Player's AbilitiesCurrently, each player has their own unique development deck. No one will care about what another player develops.Based on the abolve design, one deck will likely be superior to the others. It would be interesting to take 2-3 developments that belong to other players as your own. This could create crazy combos and make player's more interested in what the others are doing.3. Global QuestsThis will give something that everyone will fight over for VP. E.g. Save Ciri. Pay 3 Blue Leads, 3 Purple Leads and 3 Red Leads for 12 VP. Only completable once."
