76561197972483399,Not Recommended,303800,17410879,"Posted: 6 August, 2015",all,Hamburger!,"I love board games, and I love video games -- so I should love this, right? I mean, I loved Talisman... and this looks even cooler! Sadly, no. This game PRETENDS to have three equal mechanics to it (diplomacy, magic, and combat) but the only thing that really matters is combat. Game ends when any player completes a pre-set number of quests, but the person who finishes the most quests isn't the winner -- the winner is the person with the most victory points. What's the most reliable way of making victory points you ask? Why in combat of course! Every turn there is likely to be a combat, and many of the combats give VP... because of this, it is possible for the combat characters (really just Geralt, because he's the best fighter) to lap all adversaries on VP even if he doesn't come CLOSE to finishing as many quests. This game is like going to a dance contest and realizing you're also going to be judged on your attire, which is okay I guess BUT WAIT... you're ALSO going to be judged on a juggling routine... and somebody else is an expert juggler. Seriously? Keep walking."
