,Not Recommended,303800,13946330,"Posted: 11 January, 2015",all,Tai,"Not that great of a board game unfortunately. I like long adventure board games (such as Runebound and World Of Warcraft the Boardgame) and this was just kind of boring. Half way through the game I was just wanting the game to end and when it finally did end all I did was look to the ceiling and sigh heavily saying, ""finally!"".Some issues I specifically had:-Tutorial, it has you watch the first tutorial and that is all it tells you, next thing the game asks is if you want to play offline or online. Turns out there is like a dozen more tutorial videos in the main screen's menu though I didn't know that as it doesn't really make it easy to know.--At least the rule book you can access in game isn't that bad.-You can't tell what is going on in opponents turn. AI opponents take their turn really quickly with cards and effects happening all over the place but it still takes the 3 of them at least a minute to get through their turns, So the game might as well be single player game with 1-2 minute lag between turns because that is what it amounted to. What the opponents were doing didn't really matter other than the automated ""bad stuff"" that happens to you on the beginning of your turn from their Foul Fates and you don't have to pay attention for any--The activity log always being up on their turns would help, the monster that an opponent is fighting always being up on the left side of the battle screens would help too to know what is going on and what just happened to them. Especially on the battle results screen so I don't have to specifically try and remember what his negative effects for losing were.-SO MUCH bad stuff happening to you every turn, feels like you have no control over it because so much happens every turn.--It actually got to a point in my game where I had something like 10 turns where I was stuck unable to do anything but rest every turn from all the bad stuff I was suffering every single turn. Foul fates laying down more foul fates, wounds, deadly wounds. Foul fates from other players constantly. Monsters that have bad effects from just fighting them (more foul fates and wounds). More monsters spawning. On and on and on.-----90% of every turn was dealing with bad stuff happening from foul fates or other player's foul fates.-A few little glitchy spots where music cut out for a few minutes and sometimes the game wouldn't detect I had something I could do, had to restart the game once since it literally wouldn't let me take an action. And several times where I had a witcher sign but the game didn't think so then all of a sudden 30 seconds later it would say ""oh, you do have one, ok you can use it now"".-AI are really dumb at times, I'd see them use a spell/card that gives them more defense dice...then not use the dice and somehow fail the combat's defence section. Rather often too. I won my game but it took over 2 hours for a game that the main screen said should be 45 minutes, some of that may have been me not knowing how to best play but man is that a difference.Wouldn't recommend the game. Maybe I just had a really bad first game but it certainly wasn't no 45 minutes long 3-quest game. Second half of the game really felt like it was dragging on. And the game didn't feel much like an adventure game, you don't really power up your characer other than from development cards and those you can just get every turn without doing anything (literally the only way to get them is using an action to draw 2 keep 1), no gear from quests or looting monsters, no new powers really from leveling up type of stuff. Just spam development cards to get what powers you want then move around trying to collect a dozen investigation tokens of certain colors and hope the piles of bad stuff happening to you ever turn doesn't hinder you tooo much.And hey, I only played a single-player vs 3 AI game, maybe when playing multiplayer with actual other people it will get better. Though I worry about downtimes greatly increasing in that case."
