76561197960581827,Recommended,303800,20128265,"Posted: 30 December, 2015",all,[Hoyah] Phenakist,"I will start off by saying I have the boardgame, it is fantastic. I think the game does need work, but as it stands it is an enjoyable experience.The boardgame does have its advantages over the computerised title due to different rule sets that people have made for the witcher which fixes some 'issues' (opinion) with the lack of player on player interaction, as it is more of a solitary experience.That being said, there are some glaring issues with the pc version. I have come across some very odd encounters that I can only explain as bugs.- There is a creature that tells the player ''before rolling place a foul token in an adjacent region''What happens instead is the game forces you to place a foul token on your own player.--EDIT--This happens when all of your adjacent regions already have foul fates on them. That being said, the game at the time does a poor job of explaining that, and glosses over it immediately, forcing you to place a token on yourself.- There is a card that tells you if you have a 'vauble information' card you can trade it for 3 leads. The problem is that this doesn't appear to be a choice, despite the text. If you do have a valuable information card, you have held on to for other reasons, it will take it away from you and assume its the choice you wanted to make.- I swear I have had an instance of a card telling me 'x' or 'y' but it has done both, but I cannot recall 100% so maybe it didnt happen (I swear it did)I will be reporting these issues with picture examples when I get the chance and will update this if there are fixes.As it stands I would still recommend this title as it is fantastic to play. especially on sale currently for £2.09!Great boardgame from great developers"
,Recommended,303800,20146856,"Posted: 31 December, 2015",all,Eadgar,"I should mention that I also have the physical board game and have played it with friends.As a singleplayer experience, this is a decent game. It's meant to be role-played, you have to read the quests to feel any kind of depth. The formula is actually very close to the actual Witcher games: you have a main quest and some side quests. As you try to finish the main quest you get sidetracked with tasks and character development and do other things. Being a computer game, you don't have to keep track of the game rules that much, the game does it for you, so you have more time to concentrate on the fights and quests.As a multiplayer experience I feel that it's not that fun, though. There is very little player interaction, so there's no point in it being a multiplayer experience really. You might as well play alone without even any AI players.Some of the mechanics could have been improved, there are no keyboard shortcuts, which prevents effective Steam Controller use (mouse only).But overall I think it's a quaint little game, Witcher fans will enjoy it."
